% METHODS
% <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
\clearpage
\section{Materials and Methods}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Common garden setup
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection*{Common garden setup and data collection}
We collected seeds from 18 species of deciduous trees and shrubs from four provenances across a 3.5$^{\circ}$ latitudinal gradient (Figure \ref{fig:mapProv}; Table \ref{tab:provs}) in 2014-2015, germinated them following standard germination protocols and grew them to seedlings \citep{baskin_seeds_2014}. In the spring of 2017, we planted the seedlings outside at the Weld Hill Research Building at the Arnold Arboretum in Boston MA (42.30\degree N, 71.13\degree W). Plots were regularly weeded and watered throughout the duration of the study and were pruned in the autumn of 2020 \citep{buonaiuto_early_2026}. 

For the years 2018-2020, we monitored leaf phenology for all individuals in the common garden once or twice per week from February to December; the exact frequency varied within and across years (for more details, see Figure \ref{fig:phenoTimeSeries}). For this, we used a modified BBCH scale to observe two phenological stages: leafout which we defined as: BBCH 15 and budset as BBCH 102; \citep{finn_general_2007,buonaiuto_early_2026}. We had a total of \Sexpr{nrow(empfullsos)} leafout and \Sexpr{nrow(empfulleos)} budset observations (which we refer to as the `full datasets'), but for some individual trees in certain years we did not have both events; thus our total of matched full growing season duration (which we refer to as the `restricted dataset') is \Sexpr{nrow(emp)} observations.  

In the spring of 2023, we collected tree ring samples from tree species with high survivorship. Thus, we have four species in the \textit{Betulaceae} family : Grey alder (\textit{Alnus incana}), Yellow birch (\textit{Betula alleghaniensis}), Paper birch (\textit{Betula papyrifera}) and Grey birch (\textit{Betula populifolia}). We collected cross-sections on 78 individuals by cutting the trunk above the root collar, and cores on 43 individuals using standard dendrochronological methods \citep{cook_methods_1990}, for a total of 81 individual trees (Table \ref{tab:provs}). We stored the cores in modified plastic straws to promote aeration and left them to dry with the cross-sections at ambient temperature for three months. 

% Provenance map
\begin{figure}[!ht]
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{/Users/christophe_rouleau-desrochers/github/wildchrokie/analyses/figures/empiricalData/mapSourcePop.pdf}
\caption{Provenance where the seeds were sourced from is depicted as circles, while the diamond denotes the location of the common garden. The common garden location is where the study took place at the Weld Research Building (Boston, MA). The colors of the dots match the model estimates of Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotasite}.}
\label{fig:mapProv}
\end{figure}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Sample processing, imaging and measuring
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection*{Sample processing, imaging and measuring}
We mounted cores on wooden mounts and sanded both the cores and cross-sections using progressively finer sandpaper grits (150, 300, 400, 600, 800, 1000), then scanned the cores and cross-sections at a resolution of 6250 dpi with a high-resolution tree ring scanner \citep{fong_tim_2026}. Using the digitized images, we measured ring widths with ImageJ \citep{schneider_nih_2012} at three standard locations for each cross-section (at {120\degree} from each other, averaging the three measurements to yield one ring width per year, per individual), and one ring width for each core. When we had cross-sections ($n = 78$) and cores ($n = 43$) for an individual, we used only the measurement from the cross-sections ($n = 81 $). 

We performed visual cross dating. This consists of assigning a calendar year to each ring and comparing the year-to-year growth variation and anomalies across replicates of the same species \citep{cook_methods_1990}. We did not perform statistical crossdating or detrending because our chronologies (number of years of data) were extremely short \citep{radenPotentialIntraannualDensity2020a} and showed no evidence of consistent allometric trends (Figure \ref{fig:allom}). We controlled for effects of different years by including `year' in our models (see equation \ref{eq:mainMdl} in `Data analyses' below).

\subsection*{Data analyses}
To understand how growth shifted with season length, we used Bayesian hierarchical models, estimating how growth, measured as ring width, covaried with season length, measured in four different ways: GDD, GSL, SOS and EOS. We calculated the thermal season using growing degree days (GDD; mean daily temperature above 5\degree C) accumulated between leafout and budset, and the calendar season (or growing season length; GSL) as the number of days between leafout and budset. Finally, we used leafout for the start of season (SOS) and budset for the end of the season (EOS) as separate predictors that represent the boundaries of the growing season. For interpretability, we report ring width change in \% with the number of GDDs accumulated in an average week (seven days) in May (day of year 121 to 150 from 2018 to 2020), for the thermal season, and ring width change per week of season length, leafout and budset for GSL, SOS and EOS, respectively. We report effects when the 90\% UI do not overlap with zero and consider a trend if the 50\% UI do not overlap with zero.

For daily climate data across all the years of phenological sampling (2018-2020), we combined two sources. For 2018 and 2019, we used data from the climate station located at Weld Hill research station \citep{arnoldarboretum_weather_2026}. Because the data were not available for that station after August 2020, we used data from the weather station `Boston (Weld Hill)' of the Network for Environment and Weather Applications (NEWA) for the whole year in 2020 \citep{carroll_network_2026}. We used the North American Drought Monitor Maps to determine drought occurrence across years at our study location and used the proposed drought intensity index to qualify the presence of moderate, severe or extreme droughts \citep{nationalcentersforenvironmentalinformationncei_north_2026}. 

For each predictor, we estimated its effect on observed ring width ($i$, denoting each observation) for each tree ($treeid$) in each year ($year$) as:

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned} 
ln(ringwidth)_i &\sim Normal(\mu, \sigma_y) \\
\mu &= \alpha + \alpha_{\text{species}} + \alpha_{\text{prov}} + \alpha_{\text{treeid}} + \alpha_{\text{year}} + \beta_{species} \times \text{season predictor} \\
\alpha_{\text{prov}} &\sim Normal(0, \sigma_{\alpha \, \text{prov}}) \\
\alpha_{\text{treeid}} &\sim Normal(0, \sigma_{\alpha \, \text{treeid}}) \\
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:mainMdl}
\end{equation}

This model estimates a species-specific effect of each season length predictor (e.g. GDD) on growth ($\beta_{species}$), while also controlling for other variation due to species ($\alpha_{species}$), provenance ($\alpha_{prov}$), individual tree ($\alpha_{treeid}$) and year ($\alpha_{year}$). We ran the models using both natural units, and also using scaled predictors \citep[via $z$-scoring.][]{gelman_data_2006} to allow for direct comparison of effect sizes across different metrics. We report estimates as means and 90\% uncertainty intervals (UI).  

We used weakly informative priors for all models (increasing the priors by 2$\times$ for the $z$-scored models did not qualitatively affect the results). We ran four chains with 2000 warm-up and 2000 sampling iterations each, for a total of 8000 sampling iterations and checked output diagnostics: chains had no divergent transitions, $\hat{R}$ values below 1.01, and effective sample sizes ($n_{\text{eff}}$) greater than 10\% of the model iterations. We also fit the models for SOS and EOS using both the restricted ($n =$ \Sexpr{nrow(emp)}) and full datasets for each predictor (SOS $n =$ \Sexpr{nrow(empfullsos)} and EOS $n =$ \Sexpr{nrow(empfulleos)}. We wrote our models using Stan \citep{carpenter_stan_2017} with the rstan package version 2.32.7 \citep{standevelopmentteam_rstan_2025} to run the Stan code in R. 

In addition, we compared the relative effect of an extension in the SOS versus EOS using our estimated effect of GDD (Equation \ref{eq:mainMdl}). To do this, we averaged the GDD (mean daily GDD from 2005 to 2025) accumulated seven days before the median leafout (for SOS) and after the median budset (for EOS), for each species, across all years of our dataset. Then, with our estimated parameters, we report the \% effect of GDD on growth for an extended SOS and EOS: $\% \Delta \text{ring width} = (e^{\beta*GDD_{extSOS/EOS}}-1) \times 100$.

Because ring widths decrease with age---particularly with young trees---we also ran the models using basal area increment (BAI) as the response variable. This allows for a more representative portrayal of annual growth increment by using the total ring area, instead of its width alone. To calculate BAI we summed each ring width separately at the three distinct locations on the cross sections yielding three radii from pit to bark. We then calculated the area of each ring by subtracting the radius from the inner ring from the outer ring: $\pi \times (\text{inner radius}^2 - \text{outer radius}^2)$, and averaged across the three BAI for each ring. 


% <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
% RESULTS
% <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
% \clearpage
\section{Results}
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Info
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Our dataset comprised four deciduous tree species from four sites with leaf phenology data spanning three years (2018 to 2020) for a total of 
\Sexpr{nrow(empfullsos)} leafout and 
\Sexpr{nrow(empfulleos)} budset observations, yielding 
\Sexpr{nrow(emp)} complete growing seasons for 
\Sexpr{length(unique(emp$treeid))} individuals. At the common garden location, the mean summer temperature was similar across years, with 2019 being the coolest 
(\Sexpr{wcjja$tmeanmean[wcjja$year == 2019]}$^\circ$C), 2020 the hottest 
(\Sexpr{wcjja$tmeanmean[wcjja$year == 2020]}$^\circ$C), and 2018 in between 
(\Sexpr{wcjja$tmeanmean[wcjja$year == 2018]}$^\circ$C). There was no drought for those three years, except in 2020, when a moderate summer drought (June-August) ramped up to a severe drought in September \citep{nationalcentersforenvironmentalinformationncei_north_2026}.
The calendar and thermal seasons ranged from 
\Sexpr{min(emp$pgsGSL)} days and 
\Sexpr{round(min(emp$pgsGDD5),1)} GDD ({\Ball} in 
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$pgsGSL)]}) to 
\Sexpr{max(emp$pgsGSL)} days and 
\Sexpr{round(max(emp$pgsGDD5),1)} GDD ({\Ainc} in 
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$pgsGSL)]}; Figure \ref{fig:wcboxplotPred}a and b). 
The earliest leafout was
\Sexpr{emp$loCal[which.min(emp$leafout)]} ({\Ainc} in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$leafout)]}) and the latest,
\Sexpr{emp$loCal[which.max(emp$leafout)]} (also {\Ainc}, but in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$leafout)]}; Figure \ref{fig:wcboxplotPred}c). The earliest budset was 
\Sexpr{emp$bsCal[which.min(emp$budset)]} ({\Ball} in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$budset)]}) and the latest, 
\Sexpr{emp$bsCal[which.max(emp$budset)]} ({\Ainc} in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$budset)]}; Figure \ref{fig:wcboxplotPred}d. Finally, annual ring widths across years varied from 
\Sexpr{min(emp$lengthMM)} mm ({\Ball} in 
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$lengthMM)]}) to 
\Sexpr{max(emp$lengthMM)} mm ({\Bpop} in 
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$lengthMM)]}; Figure \ref{fig:wcboxplotRW}).  


%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Question 1
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Longer growing seasons increased growth for all species, but varied depending on the metric used to measure it. We report estimates as means and 90\% uncertainty intervals (UI) that correspond to ring width change in \% per one week unit (see `Data analyses' section in Methods for more details).
Warmer thermal seasons increased growth for Paper birch (\textit{Betula papyrifera}; $\beta =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_gdd_per, "B. papyrifera")}), Grey birch (\textit{Betula populifolia}; $\beta =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_gdd_per, "B. populifolia")}), and Yellow birch (\textit{Betula alleghaniensis}; $\beta =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_gdd_per, "B. alleghaniensis")}). Grey alder (\textit{Alnus incana}) trended in the same direction ($\beta =$ 
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_gdd_per, "A. incana")}); Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}a and e; Table\ref{tab:tab_GDD}).
Unlike its response to warmer thermal season, {\Ainc} grew more with longer calendar seasons ($\beta =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_gsl_per, "A. incana")}). {\Bpap} also grew more with longer calendar seasons ($\beta =$ 
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_gsl_per, "B. papyrifera")}), while the other two \textit{Betula} did not, though they trended in the same way ({\Ball}: $\beta =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_gsl_per, "B. alleghaniensis")}, and {\Bpop}: $\beta =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_gsl_per, "B. populifolia")}; Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}b and f; Table \ref{tab:tab_GSL}). 
On a scaled axis \citep[through $z$-scoring,][]{gelman_data_2006}, the thermal and calendar season were similarly predictive (Figure \ref{fig:bsppZscored}). Results with basal area increment (BAI) for the GDD model were similar to ring width (see Table \ref{tab:BAItab}).

 
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Question 2
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Increased growth with longer seasons is often presumed to come from growth in the spring, since spring phenology has shifted much more than autumn phenology. Yet, we found most species grew more with a later end of season, and only one species grew more with an earlier start of season ({\Ainc} (one of the two species for which a longer calendar season increased growth: $\beta =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_sos_per, "A. incana")}; Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}c and g; Table \ref{tab:tab_GSL}). {\Bpop} trended in the opposite direction ($\beta =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_sos_per, "B. populifolia")}; Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}c and g; Table \ref{tab:tab_EOS}). {\Ball}, which did not grow more with a longer calendar season, grew less with an earlier start of season ($\beta =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_sos_per, "B. alleghaniensis")}; Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}c and g; Table \ref{tab:tab_SOS})---but more with a later end of season ($\beta =$ 
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_eos_per, "B. alleghaniensis")}). Alongside {\Ball}, two other species grew more with a later end of season ({\Bpop}: $\beta =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_eos_per, "B. populifolia")}, and {\Bpap}: $\beta =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_eos_per, "B. papyrifera")}; Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}d and h; Table \ref{tab:tab_EOS}), with the latter being the only one of those three that also grew more with longer calendar season. The estimates were unchanged when using the full (SOS: $n =$
\Sexpr{nrow(empfullsos)} and EOS: $n =$
\Sexpr{nrow(empfulleos)}) or restricted datasets ($n =$ 
\Sexpr{nrow(emp)}; Figure \ref{fig:wcSOSEOScomparison}a).

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Comparison between GSL and GDD at both start and end of season
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
These results suggest that a later EOS contributes more to growth than an earlier start of season, which could be due to the warmer days at the end of the season. Supporting this, we found that the addition of an estimated 7 days at the EOS increased growth across all species by 
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_eosgain_mu, "all")}, compared to an increase of
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(b_sosgain_mu, "all")} from an earlier SOS (estimated using our model of GDD shown in Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp},  see `Data analyses' section in Methods for more details; Table \ref{tab:phenogain}). Differences in magnitude between an extension of SOS versus EOS were similar across species (Table \ref{tab:phenogain}).

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Question 3
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
We did not find any clear effect of year on growth (2018: $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", ayear_df2$mean[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2018")])} (UI:
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", ayear_df2$p5[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2018")])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", ayear_df2$p95[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2018")])}) ring width (log(mm); henceforth `RW'); 2019: $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", ayear_df2$mean[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2019")])} (UI:
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", ayear_df2$p5[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2019")])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", ayear_df2$p95[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2019")])}) RW; 2020: $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", ayear_df2$mean[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2020")])} (UI:
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", ayear_df2$p5[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2020")])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", ayear_df2$p95[which(ayear_df2$year_name %in% "2020")])}) RW; Table \ref{tab:tab_GDD}), and there were no apparent differences in baseline growth between species ({\Ainc}: $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(aspp_df2, "A. incana")} RW; {\Ball}: $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(aspp_df2, "B. alleghaniensis")} RW; {\Bpap}: $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(aspp_df2, "B. papyrifera")} RW; {\Bpop}: $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{fmt_stat(aspp_df2, "B. populifolia")} RW; Figure \ref{fig:wcxyGDD} and \ref{fig:wcxyGSL}; Table \ref{tab:tab_GDD}). In addition, growth did not vary with provenance (Dartmouth College (NH): $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", site_df2$mean[site_df2$site_name == "Dartmouth College (NH)"])} (UI:
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", site_df2$p5[site_df2$site_name == "Dartmouth College (NH)"])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", site_df2$p95[site_df2$site_name == "Dartmouth College (NH)"])}) RW; Harvard Forest (MA): $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", site_df2$mean[site_df2$site_name == "Harvard Forest (MA)"])} (UI:
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", site_df2$p5[site_df2$site_name == "Harvard Forest (MA)"])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", site_df2$p95[site_df2$site_name == "Harvard Forest (MA)"])}) RW; St-Hippolyte (Qc): $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", site_df2$mean[site_df2$site_name == "St-Hippolyte (Qc)"])} (UI:
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", site_df2$p5[site_df2$site_name == "St-Hippolyte (Qc)"])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", site_df2$p95[site_df2$site_name == "St-Hippolyte (Qc)"])}) RW; White Mountains (NH): $\alpha =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", site_df2$mean[site_df2$site_name == "White Mountains (NH)"])} (UI:
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", site_df2$p5[site_df2$site_name == "White Mountains (NH)"])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", site_df2$p95[site_df2$site_name == "White Mountains (NH)"])}) RW; Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotasite}; Table \ref{tab:tab_GDD}). The limited variation between provenances ($\sigma = $
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", sigma_df2$mean[sigma_df2$sigma == "sigma_asite"])} (UI:
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", sigma_df2$p5[sigma_df2$sigma == "sigma_asite"])}, 
